title.narrative: Revenue Administration and Revenue Policy - Eswatini. Revenue Policy and Administration - Eswatini

description.narrative: Support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy, most importantly financial intermediation – the efficient generation and allocation of savings to their most productive use.

This award strives to support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy. More specifically, this includes Assistance is delivered via two separate projects, with the Swaziland Revenue Authority (SRA) and to the Ministry of Finance (MoF). The SRA project began in October 2019 and focuses on developing capacity in appeals, audit programs for telecommunications firms and the agricultural sector, and criminal investigations. In December 2019, two tax policy experts conducted an assessment of the capacity of MOF Fiscal Policy Unit to analyze and forecast impacts of proposed tax changes. The OTA advisors have reviewed relevant draft legislation and submitted to the Embassy Mbabane and the MoF a report analyzing the Kingdom of Eswatini Strategic Roadmap 2019-2022 and related legislative changes recently tabled in Parliament.. Project has been discontinued.. Project is suspended.

description.narrative: The official name of the Kingdom of Swaziland was changed to the Kingdom of Eswatini, or Eswatini, in April 2018. Although Eswatini takes pride in its status as a stable monarchy, the country is beset by a range of development challenges, including minimal economic growth, the prevalence of HIV/AIDS, weak government institutions, human trafficking, porous borders and transnational terrorist threats, corruption, limited media freedom, labor disputes, and high levels of gender-based violence. A lack of fiscal transparency, increasing expenditures allocated to the royal family, and questionable capital projects have increased the call for reform by donors and domestic groups. U.S. foreign assistance to Eswatini focuses on addressing the key health threat of HIV/AIDS and support for the professionalization of the Eswatini security forces through the promotion of democratic values, including respect for human rights.
